response:
```graph
digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];

    Potentiometer -> Buffer;
    Buffer -> CalibrationCircuit;
    CalibrationCircuit -> LowPassFilter;
    LowPassFilter -> AntialiasFilter;
    AntialiasFilter -> DAQInput;

}
```

```Explanations
Potentiometer - This is the sensor that converts the mechanical angle of the pendulum into an electrical signal (voltage). The potentiometer must be capable of accurately capturing the angular range of 45 to 135 degrees. It should track the angular position of the pendulum, corresponding the midpoint (90 degrees) to the center of its electrical output range.

Buffer - The buffer serves as an impedance matching device, ensuring that the potentiometer's output is not loaded by subsequent stages. This isolates the potentiometer from the rest of the signal chain and prevents the potentiometer's performance from being affected by the input impedance of the following circuits.

CalibrationCircuit - This block is used to calibrate the output of the potentiometer to ensure that the voltage output corresponds precisely to the angle range of 45 to 135 degrees. It will likely consist of an adjustable gain and offset circuit, which can be set during the calibration routine.

LowPassFilter - A low-pass filter is included to attenuate unwanted frequencies, especially to filter out 50 and 60 Hz noise that can be induced from power lines. This filter will help in cleaning up the signal before it's sampled by the DAQ system.

AntialiasFilter - Before the signal is digitized by the DAQ, an anti-aliasing filter is necessary to prevent aliasing of any high-frequency signal content that is beyond the Nyquist frequency of the DAQâ€™s sampling rate. This filter will ensure that the sampling theorem is upheld and that the digitized data represents the true signal.

DAQInput - This is the input stage of the Data Acquisition (DAQ) system that captures the conditioned analog signal from the potentiometer. The DAQ will typically convert this signal into a digital value that can be further processed or recorded.
```

